Superior Education
I spoke of superior teachers, superior
students, and superior education, as
though the word “superior" was an absolute. It is not, of course; but what I
mean by a superior teacher is someone
who believes that his discipline provides
a vehicle for education both himself and
his students, who continues to empire to
know more than he does now, who believes that students are worth his best
preparation, who has a sense of obligation to his status as a professional man,
who has a realized or developing commitment to this kind of institution, and
who has an ability to reflect all these
characteristics to his students so that,
though they may not like him personally,
they take him seriously and believe in
him as a practitioner of the discipline he
represents. Whether he writes articles
and books is somewhat bride the point.
a matter of personal drive and taste;
whether he reads to enrich himself and
thus the dimension of his preparation is
not. His views about society are also be
side the point, thus provided he does not
substitute them for the practice of his
discipline. On this matter I do not wish
to be misunderstood, N0 instructor in
times like these can escape responding
with a personal point of view to the consumer idealism or honest confusion of
his students with what is happening in
the world. That response, which comes
by way of illustration and personal comment, cannon be nearly separated from
his subject matter in class discussion or
lectures or conferences. It is the nature
of Grinnell teachers and students to articulate their social conferences, to make
themselves relevant to their age. But a
Grinnell teacher is, ﬁrss of all a prices
signal, a teacher in a discipline, not a
full time singer of a social gospel, and
in the consideration of his own integrity,
he needs to face these hard facts.
What I mean by a superior student is
someone whose high school record indicates that he is a competent learned,
who brings enough energy and poverty
to the job of learning to be educated, and
who can accept the corporations and liabilities involved in the student-teacher relationship without getting the emotional
bands and trying out that the college is
creek or thoughtless. I do not wish to say
that student complaints are always
wrong. i have no doubt that there is
some damnably full teaching going on
in this place; that students are sometimes getting short-changed by overly
casual preparation on the part of teacha
era, or by a teacher’s liability to respond with any excitement to the real
richards of his subject matter, or by his
failure to connect it with some meaning
to other disciplines so that his students
get at least a first climate at what “no
oral studies" are really all about. I am
also aware that some courses remain in
the schedule simply because they appeal
to cataloguing instances. when students
apply the word “irrelevant” to these
sorts of diseases, we ought to listen to
their complaints seriously. But if a student means by “irrelevant” some notion that a course ought primarily to
make him tell right about his feelings,
then I don’t even know how to talk With
him, except to say, with honest narrow,
that the question is really not whether
the college is relevant to him but whether he is relevant to the college.
Well Trained and Committed
The question of what is meant by a
superior education in an undergraduate
institution like this one is answered chief—
ly by bringing superior teachers and
students together and letting them have
a go at one another. chipﬂy, but not
solely. particular management does
have a part to play, provided it tests on
two assumptions: first, on the nature of
faculty conference available; and, second, on a system to control the memo
emotional phases of individual disciplines.
The first assumption is probably obvious, though I can give you a few in
stanley from our newer ventures and
changed Circumstances. Urban Studies
and Religious Studies appear to be going
concerns because they are competition
stuffed. Our Comparative Literature Program seems to me to offer great promise because we happen to have on hand
a group of well-trained and committed
young men pages to try their hand at it.
If our Department of Russian Language
and Literature is successful, it will be
because Mr. Whelan and Mr. 'pages,
with some natural assistance from Mr.
Guroff and Mr. Kulawiec, make it so.
We cannon order any of these good things
to be done, nor can we create them
simply by drawing up hardcore curriculum chargers. We have to have the
horses first, or at least simultaneously,
and then we can provide the administrative and moral entertainment to make
them go.
Accountability
My second assumption, that of con
drilling the preprolessional phases oi
individual disciplines, is more complicated. There is something to be said
for not controlling it. For one thing,
an individual discipline which does not
consist of people with strong professional
pride and energy is not worth much to
begin with. For another, the liberal arts
general education concept has always
been in trouble with those of its practitioners who in trailer to teach everything end up teaching nothing. For still
another, graduate school societies, in
suite of the public wrestling of their means
to the contrary, still like to see strong
pre-professional courses of study in the
transcripts of their baccalaureate apply—
wants. A college such as this one, with a
strongly professionally oriented faculty
and a substantial number of students
bound for graduate or professional school
might survive a long time by simply
turning the decisions for educational policy over to individual departments. The
result would be a narrow but quite
likely, in such terms, a superior educa
tion. But such a definition of "superior"
is not the double virtual, at least potentially, of both generation and specialist; and this means that a system of
checksrand-balanced to keep matters in
equilibrium has to be allowed to funds
tion. This system functions here in the
recommendations of the additional educational policy committees, in the care
fun considerations of the Executive
Council about both personnel appointments and course changes, and in the
total faculty discussion and debate about
graduation requirements. This total faculty review, though sometimes wearir
some, is perhaps the most crucial element in the system. It tests on my conviction, which is sometimes shared but
never wholly displayed, that the wisdom
of the total faculty in educational mats
term affecting the basic direction of the
College is founder than that of an individual department or divided. It seems
to me that the harley amendment to the
Executive Council’s motion to english
the comprehensive examination require
ment is a Case in point. Individual disciplines know, or ought to know, how to
device the most effective ways to examine their students, But they ought to
be required to justify the pedagogy of
these devices to representatives of the
whole college. This kind of accountability
gives the College the opportunity to
keep its educational policy decisions in
equilibrium. For even if that equilibrium
is fretful and constantly applicable, we
can always have at hand the ways and
means to readjust it.
A good many questions are implied in
my remarks, and knowing this faculty
and student body, I do not doubt that
questions will be raised. And so they
should be. Whatever changes in detail or
possibilities may be wise or necessary
at its edges, my central position is that
our concern for professionalism in our
teachers, for academic orientation in our
students, and for purpose and control
in our educational policy has to represent our first priority and obligation
and has to have first call on our emerging.
Emotional Climate
